names:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"HARCOUET","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the places in Eure and Calvados named Harcourt, from Old French <i>cour(t)</i> ‘court, farmyard’ (see   Court  ) with an obscure first element. This surname is very rare in France.","English: habitational name from either of two places in Shropshire named Harcourt. The one near Cleobury Mortimer gets the name from Old English <i>heafocere</i> ‘hawker, falconer’ + <i>cot</i> ‘hut, cottage’; the one near Wem has as its first element Old English <i>hearpere</i> (see   Harper  ).","History: The surname of French origin (see 1 above) is listed along with the equally rare or even extinct variants or altered forms <i>Haraucourt</i>, <i>Herancourt</i>, and <i>Héraucourt</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."],"variants":[{"name":"Court","meanings":["English: topographic or occupational name from Middle English <i>curt</i>, <i>court</i> ‘large house’ (a word of the same ultimately Latin origin as 2 below), denoting someone who lived or worked in a manor house or castle, a courtly retainer.","French: topographic name from Old French <i>co(u)rt</i> ‘court, farmyard’ (from Latin <i>cohors</i>, <i>cors</i>, genitive <i>cohortis</i>, <i>cortis</i> ‘court, farmyard, enclosure’).","English and French: nickname for a physically small man, or ironically for a large man, from the adjective Middle English <i>curt</i>, Old French <i>co(u)rt</i> ‘short, small’ (from Latin <i>curtus</i> ‘curtailed, truncated, cut short, broken off’). Compare French   Lecourt  ."]}]},{"name":"Rollon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of <i>Roul</i>, the Old French version of   Rolf .  This form appears regularly in Latin documents of the Middle Ages, but does not seem to have been used in everyday vernacular contexts. It is the form by which the first Duke of Normandy (  <i>c.</i>860–932 ) is generally known. He was a Viking who, with his followers, settled at the mouth of the Seine and raided Paris, Chartres, and elsewhere. By the treaty of  St Clair  he received the duchy of Normandy from  Charles III , on condition that he should receive Christian baptism. Use of this name in English families in modern times seems to be a consciously archaistic revival."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Rollon de HARCOUET was born about 8 January 1138, in Saint-Hilaire-du-Harcouët, Manche, Normandy, France. He had at least 1 daughter with Blanche de DOL. He died on 8 January 1203, at the age of 65."},"et":{"ABT 08 JAN 1138–8 Jan 1203":"umbes 8. jaanuar 1138–8. jaanuar 1203","1152–Female":"1152–Surnud","1168–1234":"1168–1234","1138–1203":"1138–1203","1138":"1138","1203":"1203","8 Jan 1203":"8. jaanuar 1203","1234":"1234","1168":"1168","1152":"1152","about 1168":"umbes 1168","ABT 08 JAN 1138":"umbes 8. jaanuar 1138","France":"Prantsusmaa","Saint-Hilaire-du-Harcouët, 50484, Manche, Basse-Normandie, FRANCE":"Saint-Hilaire-du-Harcouët, Manche, Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"ABT 08 JAN 1138–8 Jan 1203":"noin 8. tammikuuta 1138–8. tammikuuta 1203","1152–Female":"1152–Kuollut","1168–1234":"1168–1234","1138–1203":"1138–1203","1138":"1138","1203":"1203","8 Jan 1203":"8. tammikuuta 1203","1234":"1234","1168":"1168","1152":"1152","about 1168":"noin 1168","ABT 08 JAN 1138":"noin 8. tammikuuta 1138","France":"Ranska","Saint-Hilaire-du-Harcouët, 50484, Manche, Basse-Normandie, FRANCE":"Saint-Hilaire-du-Harcouët, Manch